orking and results of six years of research on religious individualisation. It demonstrates the independence of individualisation and modernisation. It has proved that religion is a motor of individualisation. And it has proved that the wide range of phenomena under the umbrella term of 'individualisation' are to be found in many premodern societies, in India for instance as much as in Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aIndividualismxReligious aspectsxHistory. 0aSelfxReligious aspectsxHistory. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aAlbrecht, Janico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBjørn Parson, Rahul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDegelmann, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuchs, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGasparini, Valentino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinkenbach, Antje, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulsow, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulsow, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOtto, Bernd-Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatzelt, Maik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetridou, Georgia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaja, Rubina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRie